        "style": "dark",
        "align": "right",
        "image": {
            "url": "https://vc4test.blob.core.windows.net/blogs/Group 14 (1).svg"
        },
        "content": "<p>Purchasing the right amount of inventory stock is only the beginning. It&#39;s always important to keep carrying costs in mind, which are attached to all products you buy. The larger the inventory you have, the more you&#39;ll be spending on storage, while increasing your risk of having products going out-of-date. Good news is there is an equation that helps you with this - the Economic Order Quantity (EOQ) formula.</p>\n\n<p>Economic Order Quantity is a formula that helps calculate how many units your business should be adding to its inventory in order to reduce the total costs of inventory management &ndash; including factors like order costs, holding costs, and shortage costs. There are several EOQ calculators you can find online to assist in your calculations.</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n",
        "url1": null,
